15 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
16 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1151.25a of Title 59, unless
17 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
18 A. Except as otherwise provided in the Roofing Contractor
19 Registration Act, on and after July 1, 2026, every roofing
20 contractor, except for those defined in subsection G of this
21 section, offering to engage in or engaging in performing residential
22 roofing contractor work in this state shall be required to receive a
23 residential roofing endorsement. To receive a residential roofing
24 endorsement the roofing contractor shall be required to take and
Req. No. 13020 Page 16

1 succ essfully pass a residential roofing examination approved under
2 the provisions of this act with a minimum score of seventy percent
3 (70%), and be in compliance with all other provisions of the act and
4 rules thereof before acting or being endorsed as a residential
5 roofing contractor. For applicants who have been registered and in
6 good standing with the Construction Industries Board before July 1,
7 2026, there will be a twelve-month grandfathering-in period from
8 July 1, 2026, to either pass the exam or complete an additional ten
9 (10) hours of continuing education credits to be granted a
10 residential roofer endorsement.
11 B. Examinations for a residential roofer endorsement shall be
12 uniform and practical in nature and sufficiently strict to test the
13 qualifications and fitness of the applicants for endorsement.
14 Examinations shall be in whole or in part in writing. Examinations
15 shall be offered at least monthly; dates, times, and locations are
16 to be determined by the registrar or third-party vendor with
17 approval of the registrar.
18 C. Any applicant initially failing to pass the examination
19 shall not be permitted to take another examination for a period of
20 thirty (30) days. Any applicant subsequently failing to pass the
21 examination shall not be permitted to take another examination for a
22 period of ninety (90) days. However, in a declared state of
23 emergency, the examination shall be available as often as possible
24 as determined by the registrar.
